326 B. o. Rome gave good terms to Campanian Greeks, and Palaeopolis surrendered.

325—322. Samnium was overrun and penetrated by Roman armies; and being decidedly worsted the Samnites humbly sued for peace⁷ sending back Roman prisoners and property taken in the war. Their general, Brutulus Papius, the chief of their war-party, slew himself to avoid being given up, and his countrymen sent his dead body and goods to Rome. But the Romans haughtily rejected their offers and sent bac-k all but their own belongings, and prepared to renew the war. Upon which the Samnites, inspired by their new general, C. Pontius, began to take energetic measures for sels-defence.

Such is the position of affairs at the beginning of 321 B. c.‚ the year at which Lixy's ninth book starts.
